# Financial Reconciliation Process

## Overview

Financial reconciliation ensures that invoices, payments, and retailer deductions align with operational shipment records. This process confirms that revenue from wholesale transactions is accurately recorded and collected.

Reconciliation helps identify discrepancies between expected payments and received payments.

---

## Purpose

The reconciliation process helps organizations:

• confirm payment accuracy  
• detect invoice disputes  
• identify chargebacks or deductions  
• reconcile financial records with operational activity  

This process protects financial transparency and operational accountability.

---

## Reconciliation Activities

Common reconciliation tasks include:

• matching invoices to purchase orders  
• confirming shipped quantities  
• verifying retailer payments  
• identifying deductions or adjustments  
• validating payment application in financial systems  

Each task ensures financial records reflect actual business activity.

---

## Data Sources

Reconciliation relies on multiple operational and financial data sources such as:

• ERP financial records  
• invoice documentation  
• retailer remittance statements  
• shipment confirmation records  

Cross-checking these sources ensures financial accuracy.

---

## Issue Resolution

When discrepancies are identified, finance and operations teams work together to determine the cause.

Common reconciliation issues include:

• pricing discrepancies  
• shipment quantity mismatches  
• invoice transmission errors  
• unauthorized deductions  

Resolving these issues maintains financial integrity.

---

## Monitoring and Reporting

Organizations often monitor financial reconciliation performance through metrics such as:

• invoice accuracy rate  
• deduction frequency  
• payment cycle time  
• unresolved dispute volume  

These metrics help organizations improve financial processes.

---

## Final Note

Financial reconciliation ensures that operational activity translates into accurate financial outcomes. Close coordination between operations and finance teams supports reliable revenue recognition and payment tracking.
